com.urbancode.ubuild.scripting.wrappers
Class WorkflowCaseWrapper

java.lang.Object
  com.urbancode.ubuild.scripting.wrappers.WrapperBase
      com.urbancode.ubuild.scripting.wrappers.WorkflowCaseWrapper

public class WorkflowCaseWrapper
extends WrapperBase

Scripting class to give limited access to WorkflowCase information. This is exposed as 'workflow' in some notification scripts.

Examples:

To get the name of the process execution: 

    workflow.getName()
To get the id of the process execution: 
    workflow.getId()
To get the project associated with the process execution: 
    workflow.getProject()
To get the build life associated with the process execution: 
    workflow.getBuildLife()
To get the status of the process execution: 
    workflow.getStatus()
To check if the process execution has a success status: 
    workflow.statusIsSuccess()
To check if the process execution is complete: 
    workflow.isComplete()
To get the formatted start date of the process execution: 
    workflow.getStartDate()
To get the formatted end date of the process execution: 
    workflow.getEndDate()
To get the formatted duration of the process execution: 
    workflow.getDuration()
To get the process execution from the previous build life: 
    workflow.getPrevious()
To get a list of the job traces on the process execution: 
    workflow.getJobTraceList()
To get the list of source configs available to the process execution: 
    workflow.getSourceConfigs()
To get the first source config available to the process execution: 
    workflow.getSourceConfigs()[0]
To get a link to the process execution: 
    workflow.getUrl()
If you are using velocity scripts for Notification Templates, you don't have to use the full method name for getters: 
    workflow.Name
    workflow.Id
    workflow.Project
    workflow.BuildLife
    workflow.Status
    workflow.StartDate
    workflow.EndDate
    workflow.Duration
    workflow.Previous
    workflow.JobTraceList
    workflow.SourceConfigs
    workflow.Url
If you are trying to retrieve some process execution properties in a process, you would prefix the property with 'originatingProcess/' For example, to get the status for a process execution: 
    ${p:originatingProcess/status}
To get information like the project name from a process execution, you might need to chain some of these calls together. First, you would have to get the project and then get the name. For example: 
    ${p:originatingProcess/project/name}
To get all property values based on the property name, you can use the functions startsWith, contains and matches: 
    ${p:fn:startsWith(originatingProcess/properties, 'prefix')}
    ${p:fn:contains(originatingProcess/properties, 'text')}
    ${p:fn:matches(originatingProcess/properties, 'prefix.*')}
